{"key":"post-16137420","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>16137420</id>\n<content>Fruits from some strains are barely attached to the substrate and as A.S. said they tend to fall over.&amp;nbsp; With these, go ahead and twist them off.&amp;nbsp;  &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Other strains form individuals and clusters that are firmly attached to the substrate mass, and if you twist-and-pull it will leave a large divot.&amp;nbsp; When you have fruits like these(which are more common) they should be cut off.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Let's not repeat the myth that the leftover stem butts rot.&amp;nbsp; They don't.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>16137435</next>\n<prev>16137411</prev>\n<first>16137106</first>\n<last>27735074</last>\n<when>1335369289</when>\n<utime>04/25/12 06:54 PM</utime>\n</post>"}